ssing the new United Nations doctrine of responsibility to protect.   In the twenty-first century, intervention can take many forms: military and economic, unilateral and multilateral. Doyle's thought-provoking argument examines essential moral and legal questions underlying significant American foreign policy dilemmas of recent years, including Libya, Iraq, and Afghanistan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aIntervention (International law) 0aIntervention (International law). 0aResponsibility to protect (International law) 0aResponsibility to protect (International law). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2015z978311067250308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311053800708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300210781423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300210781.jpg  a978-3-11-053800-7  YUP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-067250-3  YUP eBook Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles